[normal]Q406 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Mark [bold]Pawsey[bold]:[bold] I want to ask about how effective 
[normal]local authorities are at managing contracts, 
[normal]in particular how effective they are at managing risk.  One of the risks to local authorities in the running of contracts is fraud.  Mr Bryce, I am not sure we have heard from you yet.  Could you tell us your view on how effective 
[normal]local authoritie
[normal]s are at managing risk, and the risk of fraud occurring in contracts in which they are involved?
[normal]Alan Bryce[bold]: S
[normal]peaki
[normal]ng from the evidence base that the commission collects, Mark made the point that our evidence base has changed.  W
[normal]e do collect data on all fraud com
[normal]mitted against local government and publish this in our annual report 
[normal]Protecting
[normal] the
[normal] Public Purse
[normal].  
[normal]We published the 2013 version only a couple of weeks ago.  I suggest it has some very
[normal] intere
[normal]sting messages in relation to how we interpret the fraud detection activities, compared with the total amount of fraud and the risks out there.  
[normal]For example, in 2013
[normal] all of local government
[normal]—local government as a whole submits the data—203 cases of procurement fraud to a value of £1.9
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]million were detected.  To put that into context, nationally all the fraud detected and committed against local government amounted to 107,000 cases, so we are talking about 0
[normal].2%
[normal].  
[normal]That is probably not unexpected in terms of the 
[normal]cases, because generally procurement frauds tend to be higher value cases but of lower volume compared with the traditional cases of fraud that local government face.
[normal]Some interesting trend data are starting to emerge.  If I take you back to 2011, there were 145 cases of detected procurement fraud, so that is a 40% increase in only a couple of 
[normal]years
[normal].  
[normal]That would tend to indicate 
[normal]a greater focus on this issue, which many organisations such as the Commission have been encouraging, but, given the potential scale of loss due to procurement fraud, it would indicate there is still some distance to go.  A number of reasons sit behind that.  
[normal]The most common explanation we have seen from local government investigators tends to fall around the specific problems of trying to identify and investigate 
[normal]procurement fraud
[normal] itself.  It is generally far more complex in more traditional areas such as housing benefit fraud.  Many of the
[normal] traditional
[normal] techniques, for example data matching and data analytics, 
[normal]d
[normal]o not apply,
[normal] and that
[normal] puts a lot of emphasis particularly on 
[normal]whistleblowing
[normal] initially to identify and investigate those frauds, and that 
[normal]start
[normal]s
[normal] to create issues around capa
[normal]bility.  Fifteen or 20 years ago most large internal audit teams in local government would have a contract audit
[normal] specialist, for example
[normal].  
[normal]Very few have that now, so do they necessarily
[normal] have the capability to tackle this type of fraud and investigate it properly?
[normal]There is also a
[normal]n issue of capacity
[normal] in relation to tackling procurement fraud, partic
[normal]ularly going forward.  Right now, many of the smaller local government bodies rely on the investigative capacity they already have in dealing with housing benefit fraud investigations.  It is an in-house team, but not entirely; some have corporate fraud teams and some have contract audit specialists.  Going forward, even though there are relatively few cases of detected fraud in relation to procurement that we are seeing, compared with the
[normal] totality
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]the capacity 
[normal]of 
[normal]local government to investigate this type of fraud
[normal] is likely to fall away consid
[normal]erably with the advent of the single fraud investigation service next year.
[normal]Q407 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Mark [bold]Pawsey[bold]:[bold] Were the figures you cited cases identified by the local authorities themselves or by auditors?
[normal]Alan Bryce[bold]: It would be a mix of all fraud detected.  The other thing that might be of interest to the Committee—the data bring this out quite clearly—is that, if we rewind a couple of years, the average value of the detected fraud case committed against local government was just over £100,000 per case.  If we go forward two years, it is just under £10,000.
[normal]Q408 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Mark [bold]Pawsey[bold]:[bold] What do we deduce from that?
[normal]Alan Bryce[bold]: I would suspect that a significant proportion of this is due to the fact we are now starting to see the impact, from a couple of years ago, of one particular type of procurement fraud arising from changes to bank mandate details, which the Committee might well be aware of, and the way in which the transparency agenda and tackling corruption have helped facilitate fraudsters to use publicly-available information to commit fraud.  I suggest that local government is responding very well by putting in place the prevention arrangements to stop those types of fraud happening now.
[normal]Q409 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Mark [bold]Pawsey[bold]:[bold] You are saying there are more cases but on average each case is significantly smaller in size, and therefore the total amount of fraud committed against local authority procurement is less than it was previously?
[normal]Alan Bryce[bold]: Not committed but detected.
[normal]Q410 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Mark [bold]Pawsey[bold]:[bold] Are local bodies good at detecting fraud?  I suppose that the judgment call I am asking you to make is how much people are getting away with.
[normal]Alan Bryce[bold]: At the start, I 
[normal]alluded
[normal] to the fact that 
[normal]detecting this 
[normal]type of fraud is very difficult.  Short of 
[normal]whistleblowing
[normal], it is very hard to find these types of fraud
[normal], despite the 
[normal]fact that there has been a lot of guidance about good practice to
[normal] assist authorities
[normal].  
[normal]There is no academi
[normal]cally robust and statistically significant estimate of the scale of procurement fraud against local government.  An estimate has been made by the National Fraud Authority.  It estimates that £876 million is the likely scale of risk of annual fraud loss in local government procurement.  
[normal]Therefore, by comparison
[normal] £1.9 million of detection in total would appear very small, but a
[normal] couple of points
[normal] are to be made here.  
[normal]One is that it suggests that even more can be done by local government.  When I talked about the amount detected
[normal] in one year, that could be
[normal] running back several years.  Therefore, the £1.9 million of detected fraud in local government in the last year is not just the total amount committed in that year.  However, when the National Fraud Authority talks about the total annual loss, that is just for one year, so it suggests that in terms of value an awful lot more can be done.
[normal]I would put down a marker in respect of that 
[normal]estimate
[normal].  That estimate is based
[normal] on an analysi
[normal]s of procurement fraud in the MO
[normal]D
[normal], not local government.  Without being an expert in procurement in the MOD, I do not know how directly comparable that is with the fraud prevention arrangements that local government have, so it might be more of an indicator at the top level, but certainly it is difficult to say how true a reflection that is.
[normal]Q411 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Mark [bold]Pawsey[bold]:[bold] In terms of management of risk
[normal], what steps could local authorities take
[normal] to improve their performance
[normal]?
[normal]Alan Bryce[bold]: 
[normal]Fraud can happen anywhere within the process of procur
[normal]ement.  Maybe I should explain that every single case of fraud committed against local government valued at over £10,000 crosses my desk.  Most of the fraud cases being detected tend to be at
[normal] the contract implementation stage
[normal].  
[normal]There are important 
[normal]issues more generally about the controls in place to prevent and detect fraud, for example 
[normal]traditional issues around segregation of duties
[normal].  
[normal]We have seen an 
[normal]ups
[normal]urge in the number of cases where the absence of supervisory controls and segregation of duties has enabled these 
[normal]fraud
