[normal]Q416 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]David [bold]Heyes[bold]:[bold] That poses two obvious questions.  What can we do to make that more likely?  How can we be more supportive of potential whistleblowers to create a more open environment?  What other things should councils be doing to open up other sources of identification of fraud?
[normal]Alan Bryce[bold]: As to 
[normal]whistleblowing
[normal], this really comes down to a fundamental issue in terms of who is doing the 
[normal]whistleblowing
[normal].  
[normal]As we have recognised in other areas,
[normal] it is important to ensure that the organisations you deal with and the staff involved, who will be the people who blow the whistle, are aware, in a local government context, of to whom they can blow the whistle, not just in their own organisation but the local authorities concerned.  I know that as part of contract arrangements some consideration is often given to what the 
[normal]whistleblowing
[normal] arrangements of the provider organisation are, but I think we could go a lot further than that.
[normal]In the end, the danger of that approach is ticking a box that virtually everybody will be able to tick—“I have some 
[normal]whistleblowing
[normal] arrangements, or a policy as such.” Any organisation would be able to say that.  What is more important is the extent to which that is embedded; the culture of staff in a private sector organisation, of which care homes are a very good example; and whether those providing the care—this goes further than fraud—would feel confident to blow the whistle to the council rather than their own organisation if they saw something of concern, and there are detrimental aspects to this for them individually.  Strengthening the requirement around that and putting greater emphasis on assurance around the 
[normal]whistleblowing
[normal] arrangements in provider organisations would be very helpful.
[normal]This Committee might not have had the chan
[normal]ce to consider it yet, but the leading 
[normal]whistleblowing
[normal] charity, Public Concern at Work, published its 
[normal]Whistleblowing
[normal] Commission report last week.  T
[normal]hey make a number 
[normal]of very helpful recommendations that address that specific point, which is wider than just fraud, and include a 
[normal]code of practic
[normal]e.  That is something 
[normal]privat
[normal]e bodies might want to consider in the future.
[normal]Keith Davis[bold]: That 
[normal]echoes wh
[normal]at we said about 
[normal]whistleblowing
[normal] in our report a couple of weeks ago.  We framed it in terms of public sector procuring authorities seeing it very much as part of the dialogue they are having with contractors, saying to them, “If you want to 
[normal]do business with us, we want to see your 
[normal]whistleblowing
[normal] policy; we want to
